&lt;b&gt;Reaching out to partners&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;
    &lt;!--[endif]--&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a&gt;If you are developing a new program, you
will need to contact local apprenticeships and other employers to see if they
are interested in partnering with your organization.&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;This is a chance to learn more about their recruitment needs and expectations and ways your program may be able to help them meet these. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As a reminder, you may wish to use the helpful tools above to find local apprenticeships. Some of the tools from Topic 2.1: Identifying and interpreting workforce data may also be useful.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When you are conducting partner outreach, consider these key tips:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
    &lt;/p&gt;&lt;ul&gt;
        &lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;Do your
research&lt;/b&gt;. Seek out partners with similar goals and make sure you understand their mission.&lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;Have a
strong value proposition&lt;/b&gt;. Be clear on what value the partnership would bring to everyone involved. Highlight the return on investment for employers — such as reduced recruitment costs and turnover rates. (See the next activity to get started).&lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;Have &lt;a&gt;written and
verbal pitches&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;b&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;b&gt;ready for formal and informal environments&lt;/b&gt;. Make sure to include memorable facts — such as who your participants are and your intended or actual outcomes (e.g., graduation and placement rates, increased earnings
            potential). &lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;Ask
thoughtful questions&lt;/b&gt;. What are their recruitment needs and challenges? What are their expectations for a partnership? How involved would they like to be?&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
